	abstract = {During the winter of 1991 an unusually favorable series of occultations of Io by Europa took place. We obtained infrared photometry of four of these events at the United Kingdom Infrared Telescope at wavelengths of 5.0 or 3.4 μm, in order to investigate the nature and distribution of volcanism on Io by observing the occultation of the volcanic hot spots by the limb of Europa. Observations at 3.4 μm on 1991/01/08 detected a possible small hot spot in the northern hemisphere. Observations at 5.0 μm on 1991/02/27 detected and resolved the major hot spot Loki, which had a diameter of 170 km and had three times its Voyager 1 flux, and also detected the Voyager hot spot Pele at about half its Voyager 1 flux. A 5.0-μm occultation of Pele on 1991/03/06, when Loki was not occulted, indicated no significant flux change since the week before. Infrared images of Io obtained at the NASA Infrared Telescope Facility between October 1990 and April 1991 show that the Europa occultations occurred during a period of unusually high activity at Loki. Loki showed very little thermal emission in observations between 1990/10/12 and 1990/11/27, but increased in flux by a factor of 10 in 32 days by 1991/12/29. Loki then remained bright in all observations until 1991/03/26, but had begun to fade on 1991/04/09. Such rapid variations in flux over such a large area are remarkable. Multiwavelength observations indicate that Loki increased in temperature during the brightening, and that materials hotter than 630 K were exposed at Loki. The possible "Pele-type" volcanoes Surt and Aten, unlike Pele, were not detected, with 3.8 μm flux upper limits of about 8 GW μm-1 str-1.},
